Title:
Amsi-Bypass-Powershell

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository is a collection of PowerShell-based AMSI (Antimalware Scan Interface) bypass/avoidance techniques aggregated from various public blog posts and research.  
- It targets common offensive friction where PowerShell payloads are scanned/blocked by AMSI and Defender/AV providers, and demonstrates multiple ways to disable or subvert scanning within a process/session.  
- Techniques include in-memory patching of AMSI entrypoints (e.g., AmsiScanBuffer/AmsiOpenSession), CLR/.NET method pointer manipulation and hooking, provider DLL patching (MpOav.dll), ScriptBlock AST “smuggling,” and interception of AMSI provider scan callbacks.  
- The README notes many snippets are signatured and suggests using AMSITrigger plus manual modifications/obfuscation (renaming, string replacement, runtime decode) to evade static detections.  
- Useful primarily for red teams/pentesters and malware developers for tradecraft study and prototyping; also relevant to blue teams for understanding bypass primitives and building detections around memory tampering and PowerShell internals.  
- Interesting because it consolidates a broad spectrum of AMSI bypass classes (reflection-only, patching, hooking, breakpoint-based) showing how attackers pivot between user-mode and .NET runtime manipulation.

Technical Focus:
- AMSI internals and bypass primitives (AmsiScanBuffer, AmsiOpenSession, ScanContent)
- In-memory patching via VirtualProtect/WriteProcessMemory and shellcode stubs
- .NET/CLR method pointer swapping, JIT preparation, and CLR hooking
- PowerShell ScriptBlock/AST manipulation (ScriptBlock smuggling)
- AMSI provider manipulation (MpOav.dll patching, provider scan interception)
- Hardware breakpoints + vectored exception handling to force “clean” results

Use Cases:
- Rapid testing of AMSI bypass approaches in a controlled lab
- Adapting/rewriting known bypasses to evade current signatures (manual mutation/obfuscation)
- Building offensive loaders that execute PowerShell content with reduced AMSI visibility
- Defensive research: creating detections for AMSI tampering, suspicious VirtualProtect/patch patterns, and PowerShell reflection abuse
- Training material for understanding PowerShell/AMSI attack surface and mitigations

Keywords:
AMSI, Antimalware Scan Interface, PowerShell, AmsiScanBuffer, AmsiOpenSession, System.Management.Automation, AmsiUtils, ScanContent, VirtualProtect, WriteProcessMemory, ReadProcessMemory, CLR hooking, JIT, RuntimeHelpers.PrepareMethod, reflection, ScriptBlock smuggling, AST, Vectored Exception Handler, hardware breakpoints, MpOav.dll, provider scan interception